nl_statement:
A subset $U$ of $V$ is a subspace of $V$ if and only if $U$ satisfies the following three conditions.

\textbf{additive identity}  
\quad $0 \in U$.

\textbf{closed under addition}  
\quad $u, w \in U$ implies $u + w \in U$.

\textbf{closed under scalar multiplication}  
\quad $a \in \mathbf{F}$ and $u \in U$ implies $au \in U$.

Suppose that \(V\) and \(W\) are finite-dimensional vector spaces, \(\dim V = \dim W\), and \(T\in\mathcal{L}(V,W)\).  Then
\[
T\text{ is invertible}
\;\Longleftrightarrow\;
T\text{ is injective}
\;\Longleftrightarrow\;
T\text{ is surjective}.
\]

Suppose \(T\in\mathcal L(V,W)\).  Then  
(a) \(\widetilde T\circ\pi = T\), where \(\pi\) is the quotient map of \(V\) onto \(V/(\null T)\);  
(b) \(\widetilde T\) is injective;  
(c) \(\mathrm{range}\,\widetilde T = \mathrm{range}\,T\);  
(d) \(V/(\null T)\) and \(\mathrm{range}\,T\) are isomorphic vector spaces.

Suppose \(T\in\mathcal L(V,W)\). Then
\begin{enumerate}[(a)]
  \item \((S+T)' = S' + T'\) for all \(S\in\mathcal L(V,W)\);
  \item \((\lambda T)' = \lambda T'\) for all \(\lambda\in F\);
  \item \((ST)' = T'S'\) for all \(S\in\mathcal L(W,U)\).
\end{enumerate}

Suppose \(V\) is finite-dimensional and \(U\) is a subspace of \(V\). Then
\begin{enumerate}
  \item \(U^0 = \{0\}\iff U = V;\)
  \item \(U^0 = V'\iff U = \{0\}.\)
\end{enumerate}

informal_proof:
To prove (a), we have
\[
  U^0 = \{0\}
  \;\iff\;
  \dim U^0 = 0
  \;\iff\;
  \dim U = \dim V
  \;\iff\;
  U = V,
\]
where the second equivalence follows from 3.125 and the third equivalence follows from 2.39.

Similarly, to prove (b), we have
\[
  U^0 = V'
  \;\iff\;
  \dim U^0 = \dim V'
  \;\iff\;
  \dim U^0 = \dim V
  \;\iff\;
  \dim U = 0
  \;\iff\;
  U = \{0\},
\]
where one direction of the first equivalence follows from 2.39, the second equivalence follows from 3.111, and the third equivalence follows from 3.125.

nl_statement:
Suppose \(V\) and \(W\) are finite-dimensional and \(T\in\mathcal L(V,W)\). Then
\begin{enumerate}
  \item \(\mathrm{null}\,T'=(\mathrm{range}\,T)^0;\)
  \item \(\dim\mathrm{null}\,T'=\dim\mathrm{null}\,T+\dim W-\dim V.\)
\end{enumerate}

Suppose \(V\) and \(W\) are finite-dimensional and \(T\in\mathcal L(V,W)\). Then
\[
  T\text{ is surjective}
  \;\Longleftrightarrow\;
  T'\text{ is injective}.
\]

informal_proof:
We have
\[
  T\in\mathcal L(V,W)\text{ is surjective}
  \;\Longleftrightarrow\;
  \mathrm{range}\,T = W
  \;\Longleftrightarrow\;
  (\mathrm{range}\,T)^0 = \{0\}
  \;\Longleftrightarrow\;
  \mathrm{null}\,T' = \{0\}
  \;\Longleftrightarrow\;
  T'\text{ is injective},
\]
where the second equivalence comes from 3.127(a) and the third equivalence comes from 3.128(a).

nl_statement:
Suppose \(V\) and \(W\) are finite-dimensional and \(T\in\mathcal L(V,W)\). Then
\begin{enumerate}
  \item \(\dim\mathrm{range}\,T' = \dim\mathrm{range}\,T;\)
  \item \(\mathrm{range}\,T' = (\mathrm{null}\,T)^0.\)
\end{enumerate}

Suppose \(V\) and \(W\) are finite‐dimensional and \(T\in\mathcal L(V,W)\). Then
\[
  T\text{ is injective}
  \;\Longleftrightarrow\;
  T'\text{ is surjective}.
\]

informal_proof:
We have
\[
  T\text{ is injective}
  \;\Longleftrightarrow\;
  \mathrm{null}\,T=\{0\}
  \;\Longleftrightarrow\;
  (\mathrm{null}\,T)^0=V'
  \;\Longleftrightarrow\;
  \mathrm{range}\,T'=V',
\]
where the second equivalence follows from 3.127(b) and the third equivalence follows from 3.130(b).  
Hence \(T'\) is surjective.

nl_statement:
Suppose \( p, q \in \mathcal{P}(\mathbf{F}) \) and \( T \in \mathcal{L}(V) \). Then  
\begin{itemize}
  \item[(a)] \( (pq)(T) = p(T)q(T) \);
  \item[(b)] \( p(T)q(T) = q(T)p(T) \).
\end{itemize}

Suppose \( T \in \mathcal{L}(V) \) and \( v_1, \ldots, v_n \) is a basis of \( V \). Then the following are equivalent.
\begin{itemize}
  \item[(a)] The matrix of \( T \) with respect to \( v_1, \ldots, v_n \) is upper triangular.
  \item[(b)] \( \mathrm{span}(v_1, \ldots, v_k) \) is invariant under \( T \) for each \( k = 1, \ldots, n \).
  \item[(c)] \( Tv_k \in \mathrm{span}(v_1, \ldots, v_k) \) for each \( k = 1, \ldots, n \).
\end{itemize}

Suppose \( V \) is a finite-dimensional complex vector space and \( S, T \) are commuting operators on \( V \). Then
\begin{itemize}
  \item every eigenvalue of \( S + T \) is an eigenvalue of \( S \) plus an eigenvalue of \( T \),
  \item every eigenvalue of \( ST \) is an eigenvalue of \( S \) times an eigenvalue of \( T \).
\end{itemize}

\textbf{6.6 \quad \textit{basic properties of an inner product}}

\begin{itemize}
\item[(a)] For each fixed \( v \in V \), the function that takes \( u \in V \) to \( \langle u, v \rangle \) is a linear map from \( V \) to \( \mathbb{F} \).
\item[(b)] \( \langle 0, v \rangle = 0 \) for every \( v \in V \).
\item[(c)] \( \langle v, 0 \rangle = 0 \) for every \( v \in V \).
\item[(d)] \( \langle u, v + w \rangle = \langle u, v \rangle + \langle u, w \rangle \) for all \( u, v, w \in V \).
\item[(e)] \( \langle u, \lambda v \rangle = \overline{\lambda} \langle u, v \rangle \) for all \( \lambda \in \mathbb{F} \) and all \( u, v \in V \).
\end{itemize}

informal_proof:
\begin{itemize}
\item[(a)] For \( v \in V \), the linearity of \( u \mapsto \langle u, v \rangle \) follows from the conditions of additivity and homogeneity in the first slot in the definition of an inner product.

\item[(b)] Every linear map takes \( 0 \) to \( 0 \). Thus (b) follows from (a).

\item[(c)] If \( v \in V \), then the conjugate symmetry property in the definition of an inner product and (b) show that 
\[
\langle v, 0 \rangle = \langle 0, v \rangle = \overline{0} = 0.
\]

\item[(d)] Suppose \( u, v, w \in V \). Then
\[
\langle u, v + w \rangle = \overline{\langle v + w, u \rangle}
= \overline{\langle v, u \rangle + \langle w, u \rangle}
= \overline{\langle v, u \rangle} + \overline{\langle w, u \rangle}
= \langle u, v \rangle + \langle u, w \rangle.
\]

\item[(e)] Suppose \( \lambda \in \mathbb{F} \) and \( u, v \in V \). Then
\[
\langle u, \lambda v \rangle = \overline{\langle \lambda v, u \rangle}
= \overline{\lambda \langle v, u \rangle}
= \overline{\lambda} \, \overline{\langle v, u \rangle}
= \overline{\lambda} \langle u, v \rangle.
\]
\end{itemize}

nl_statement:
Suppose \( v \in V \).
\begin{itemize}
  \item[(a)] \( \|v\| = 0 \) if and only if \( v = 0 \).
  \item[(b)] \( \|\lambda v\| = |\lambda| \|v\| \) for all \( \lambda \in \mathbb{F} \).
\end{itemize}

\begin{itemize}
  \item[(a)] \( 0 \) is orthogonal to every vector in \( V \).
  \item[(b)] \( 0 \) is the only vector in \( V \) that is orthogonal to itself.
\end{itemize}

informal_proof:
\begin{itemize}
  \item[(a)] Recall that 6.6(b) states that \( \langle 0, v \rangle = 0 \) for every \( v \in V \).
  \item[(b)] If \( v \in V \) and \( \langle v, v \rangle = 0 \), then \( v = 0 \) (by definition of inner product).
\end{itemize}

nl_statement:
Suppose \( e_1, \ldots, e_n \) is an orthonormal basis of \( V \) and \( u, v \in V \). Then
\begin{itemize}
  \item[(a)] \( v = \langle v, e_1 \rangle e_1 + \cdots + \langle v, e_n \rangle e_n \);
  \item[(b)] \( \|v\|^2 = |\langle v, e_1 \rangle|^2 + \cdots + |\langle v, e_n \rangle|^2 \);
  \item[(c)] \( \langle u, v \rangle = \langle u, e_1 \rangle \overline{\langle v, e_1 \rangle} + \cdots + \langle u, e_n \rangle \overline{\langle v, e_n \rangle} \).
\end{itemize}

Suppose \( U \) is a finite-dimensional subspace of \( V \). Then
\begin{itemize}
  \item[(a)] \( P_U \in \mathcal{L}(V) \);
  \item[(b)] \( P_U u = u \) for every \( u \in U \);
  \item[(c)] \( P_U w = 0 \) for every \( w \in U^\perp \);
  \item[(d)] \( \operatorname{range} P_U = U \);
  \item[(e)] \( \operatorname{null} P_U = U^\perp \);
  \item[(f)] \( v - P_U v \in U^\perp \) for every \( v \in V \);
  \item[(g)] \( P_U^2 = P_U \);
  \item[(h)] \( \| P_U v \| \leq \| v \| \) for every \( v \in V \);
  \item[(i)] If \( e_1, \ldots, e_m \) is an orthonormal basis of \( U \) and \( v \in V \), then
  \[
    P_U v = \langle v, e_1 \rangle e_1 + \cdots + \langle v, e_m \rangle e_m.
  \]
\end{itemize}

informal_proof:
We have
\begin{align}
\|v - P_U v\|^2 &\leq \|v - P_U v\|^2 + \|P_U v - u\|^2 \notag \\
               &= \|(v - P_U v) + (P_U v - u)\|^2 \notag \\
               &= \|v - u\|^2, \tag{6.62}
\end{align}
where the first line above holds because \( 0 \leq \|P_U v - u\|^2 \), the second line above comes from the Pythagorean theorem [which applies because \( v - P_U v \in U^\perp \) by 6.57(f), and \( P_U v - u \in U \)], and the third line above holds by simple algebra. Taking square roots gives the desired inequality.

The inequality proved above is an equality if and only if (6.62) is an equality, which happens if and only if \( \|P_U v - u\| = 0 \), which happens if and only if \( u = P_U v \).

nl_statement:
Suppose \( V \) is finite-dimensional and \( T \in \mathcal{L}(V, W) \).
\begin{itemize}
  \item[(a)] If \( T \) is invertible, then \( T^\dagger = T^{-1} \).
  \item[(b)] \( T T^\dagger = P_{\operatorname{range} T} \), the orthogonal projection of \( W \) onto \( \operatorname{range} T \).
  \item[(c)] \( T^\dagger T = P_{(\operatorname{null} T)^\perp} \), the orthogonal projection of \( V \) onto \( (\operatorname{null} T)^\perp \).
\end{itemize}

Suppose \( T \in \mathcal{L}(V, W) \). Then  
\begin{itemize}
  \item[(a)] \( (S + T)^* = S^* + T^* \) for all \( S \in \mathcal{L}(V, W) \);
  \item[(b)] \( (\lambda T)^* = \overline{\lambda} T^* \) for all \( \lambda \in \mathbb{F} \);
  \item[(c)] \( (T^*)^* = T \);
  \item[(d)] \( (ST)^* = T^* S^* \) for all \( S \in \mathcal{L}(W, U) \) (here \( U \) is a finite-dimensional inner product space over \( \mathbb{F} \));
  \item[(e)] \( I^* = I \), where \( I \) is the identity operator on \( V \);
  \item[(f)] If \( T \) is invertible, then \( T^* \) is invertible and \( (T^*)^{-1} = (T^{-1})^* \).
\end{itemize}

Suppose \( T \in \mathcal{L}(V, W) \). Then
\begin{itemize}
  \item[(a)] \( \text{null } T^* = (\text{range } T)^\perp \);
  \item[(b)] \( \text{range } T^* = (\text{null } T)^\perp \);
  \item[(c)] \( \text{null } T = (\text{range } T^*)^\perp \);
  \item[(d)] \( \text{range } T = (\text{null } T^*)^\perp \).
\end{itemize}

Suppose \( T \in \mathcal{L}(V, W) \). Then  
(a) \( T^* T \) is a positive operator on \( V \);  
(b) \( \text{null } T^* T = \text{null } T \);  
(c) \( \text{range } T^* T = \text{range } T^* \);  
(d) \( \dim \text{range } T = \dim \text{range } T^* = \dim \text{range } T^* T \).

Suppose that \( T \in \mathcal{L}(V, W) \). Then  
(a) \( T \) is injective \( \iff \) 0 is not a singular value of \( T \);  
(b) the number of positive singular values of \( T \) equals \( \dim \text{range } T \);  
(c) \( T \) is surjective \( \iff \) number of positive singular values of \( T \) equals \( \dim W \).

Suppose \( T \in \mathcal{L}(V, W) \). Then
\begin{itemize}
  \item[(a)] \( \|T\| \geq 0 \);
  \item[(b)] \( \|T\| = 0 \iff T = 0 \);
  \item[(c)] \( \|\lambda T\| = |\lambda| \|T\| \) for all \( \lambda \in \mathbb{F} \);
  \item[(d)] \( \|S + T\| \leq \|S\| + \|T\| \) for all \( S \in \mathcal{L}(V, W) \).
\end{itemize}

Suppose \( T \in \mathcal{L}(V, W) \). Then
\begin{itemize}
  \item[(a)] \( \|T\| \) is the largest singular value of \( T \);
  \item[(b)] \( \|T\| = \max\{ \|Tv\| : v \in V \text{ and } \|v\| = 1 \} \);
  \item[(c)] \( \|T\| \) is the smallest number \( c \) such that \( \|Tv\| \leq c\|v\| \) for all \( v \in V \).
\end{itemize}

Suppose \( \mathbb{F} = \mathbb{C} \) and \( T \in \mathcal{L}(V) \). Let \( \lambda_1, \ldots, \lambda_m \) be the distinct eigenvalues of \( T \). Then  
\begin{itemize}
  \item[(a)] \( G(\lambda_k, T) \) is invariant under \( T \) for each \( k = 1, \ldots, m \);
  \item[(b)] \( (T - \lambda_k I)|_{G(\lambda_k, T)} \) is nilpotent for each \( k = 1, \ldots, m \);
  \item[(c)] \( V = G(\lambda_1, T) \oplus \cdots \oplus G(\lambda_m, T) \).
\end{itemize}

Suppose \( \mathbb{F} = \mathbb{C} \) and \( T \in \mathcal{L}(V) \). Then  
(a) the characteristic polynomial of \( T \) has degree \( \dim V \);  
(b) the zeros of the characteristic polynomial of \( T \) are the eigenvalues of \( T \).

Suppose \(n > 1\) and \(\beta_1, \dots, \beta_n \in \mathbb{F}\). Then
\[
\det \begin{pmatrix}
1 & \beta_1 & \beta_1^2 & \cdots & \beta_1^{n-1} \\
1 & \beta_2 & \beta_2^2 & \cdots & \beta_2^{n-1} \\
\vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\
1 & \beta_n & \beta_n^2 & \cdots & \beta_n^{n-1}
\end{pmatrix}
= \prod_{1 \leq j < k \leq n} (\beta_k - \beta_j).
\]

informal_proof:
To prove (a), suppose \( e_1, \ldots, e_m \) and \( f_1, \ldots, f_n \) are both linearly independent lists. This linear independence and the linear map lemma (3.4) imply that there exist \( \varphi_1, \ldots, \varphi_m \in V' \) and \( \tau_1, \ldots, \tau_n \in W' \) such that
\[
\varphi_j(e_k) =
\begin{cases}
1 & \text{if } j = k, \\
0 & \text{if } j \ne k,
\end{cases}
\quad \text{and} \quad
\tau_j(f_k) =
\begin{cases}
1 & \text{if } j = k, \\
0 & \text{if } j \ne k,
\end{cases}
\]
where \( j, k \in \{1, \ldots, m\} \) in the first equation and \( j, k \in \{1, \ldots, n\} \) in the second equation.

Suppose \( \{ a_{j,k} \}_{j = 1, \ldots, m;\, k = 1, \ldots, n} \) is a list of scalars such that
\begin{align}
\sum_{k = 1}^{n} \sum_{j = 1}^{m} a_{j,k} (e_j \otimes f_k) = 0. \tag{9.75}
\end{align}
Note that \( (e_j \otimes f_k)(\varphi_M, \tau_N) \) equals 1 if \( j = M \) and \( k = N \), and equals 0 otherwise. Thus applying both sides of 9.75 to \( (\varphi_M, \tau_N) \) shows that \( a_{M,N} = 0 \), proving that
\[
\{ e_j \otimes f_k \}_{j = 1, \ldots, m;\, k = 1, \ldots, n}
\]
is linearly independent.

Now (b) follows from (a), the equation \( \dim V \otimes W = (\dim V)(\dim W) \) [see 9.72], and the result that a linearly independent list of the right length is a basis (see 2.38).
